First, I generate some points (Dogs and Cats), which are linearly seperable and let the perceptron find the seperating hyperplane, which in 2D is just a line.

Lets take a look at the convergence:

After oscillating a little bit, The perceptron converges after roughly 140 iterations. We can clearly see that it is not a steepest descent based method. Lets increase the radius of the points a little bit:

With the classes more stretched out the perceptron can actually find the hyper plane much faster. Now lets see what non-seperable classes give us:

here the hyperplane found is essentially useless. Looking at the error, shows us that the perceptron iterates and iterates and improves, and worsens until the maximum number of iterations are reached. It is not able to even find a local minimum, which makes it in its unkernelized version pretty much useless in the real world.
